Class RoutineMethod

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.github.dm.jrt.method.RoutineMethod
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    InvocationConfigurable<RoutineMethod>, InvocationConfiguration.Configurable<RoutineMethod>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    RoutineMethod.ObjectRoutineMethod

    public class RoutineMethod
extends Object
implements InvocationConfigurable<RoutineMethod>
    This class provides an easy way to implement a routine which can be combined in complex ways with other ones.

    How to implement a routine

    A routine is implemented by extending the class and defining a method taking input and output channels as parameters. The number of input and output channels can be arbitrarily chosen, moreover, any other type of parameters can be passed in any order.
    The method will be called each time a new input is passed to one of the input channels. Additionally, the method is called once when the invocation is aborted and when it completes. In the former case every input channel will behave as an aborted one (see Channel), while, in the latter, no data will be available, so, it is always advisable to verify that an input is available before reading it.
    The method parameters used as input channels are identified by the In annotation, while the output ones by the Out annotation. Channel parameters without any specific annotation will be passed as is to the target method.

    For example, a routine computing the square of integers can be implemented as follows: 

         

         final Channel<Integer, Integer> inputChannel = JRoutineCore.io().buildChannel();
         final Channel<Integer, Integer> outputChannel = JRoutineCore.io().buildChannel();
         new RoutineMethod() {

             public void square(@In final Channel<?, Integer> input,
                     @Out final Channel<Integer, ?> output) {
                 if (input.hasNext()) {
                     final int i = input.next();
                     output.pass(i * i);
                 }
             }
         }.call(inputChannel, outputChannel);
         inputChannel.pass(1, 2, 3).close();
         outputChannel.after(seconds(1)).all(); // expected values: 1, 4, 9
    The call() method returns an output channel producing the outputs returned by the target method. In the above case no output is returned (in fact, the return type is void), still the channel will be notified of the invocation abortion and completion.

    Several methods can be defined, though, be aware that the number and type of parameters are employed to identify the method to call. Any clash in the method signatures will raise an exception.

    Channels vs static parameters

    When parameters other than Channels are passed to the call() method, the very same values are employed each time a new input is available.

    For example, a routine transforming the case of a string can be implemented as follows: 

         

         final Channel<String, String> inputChannel = JRoutineCore.io().buildChannel();
         final Channel<?, String> outputChannel = new RoutineMethod() {

             public String switchCase(@In final Channel<?, String> input,
                     final boolean isUpper) {
                 if (input.hasNext()) {
                     final String str = input.next();
                     return (isUpper) ? str.toUpperCase() : str.toLowerCase();
                 }
                 return ignoreReturnValue();
             }
         }.call(inputChannel, true);
         inputChannel.pass("Hello", "JRoutine", "!").close();
         outputChannel.after(seconds(1)).all(); // expected values: "HELLO", "JROUTINE", "!"
    Note that outputs will be collected through the channel returned by the call() method.
    Note also that, when the invocation completes, that is, no input is available, the method ignoreReturnValue() is called to avoid pushing any output to the result channel. The same method can be called any time no output is produced.

    In case the very same input or output channel instance has to be passed as parameter, it is sufficient to avoid in/out annotations, like shown below: 

         

         final Channel<String, String> outputChannel = JRoutineCore.io().buildChannel();
         new MyRoutine() {

             void run(final Channel<String, ?> output) {
                 output.pass("...");
             }

         }.call(outputChannel);

    Parallel and multiple invocations

    In order to enable parallel invocation of the routine, it is necessary to provide the proper parameters to the routine method non-default constructor. In fact, parallel invocations will employ several instances of the implementing class.
    Note that, for anonymous and inner classes, synthetic constructors will be created by the compiler, hence the enclosing class, along with any variable captured inside the method, must be explicitly passed to the constructor.
    Like, for example: 
         

         final Locale locale = Locale.getDefault();
         final Channel<String, String> inputChannel = JRoutineCore.io().buildChannel();
         final Channel<?, String> outputChannel = new RoutineMethod(this, locale) {

             public String switchCase(@In final Channel<?, String> input,
                     final boolean isUpper) {
                 if (input.hasNext()) {
                     final String str = input.next();
                     return (isUpper) ? str.toUpperCase(locale) : str.toLowerCase(locale);
                 }
                 return ignoreReturnValue();
             }
         }.callParallel(inputChannel, true);
         inputChannel.pass("Hello", "JRoutine", "!").close();
         outputChannel.after(seconds(1)).all(); // expected values: "HELLO", "JROUTINE", "!"
    Or, for an inner class: 
         

         class MyMethod extends RoutineMethod {

             private final Locale mLocale;

             MyMethod(final Locale locale) {
                 super(OuterClass.this, locale);
                 mLocale = locale;
             }

             String switchCase(@In final Channel<?, String> input,
                    final boolean isUpper) {
                 if (input.hasNext()) {
                     final String str = input.next();
                     return (isUpper) ? str.toUpperCase(mLocale) : str.toLowerCase(mLocale);
                 }
                 return ignoreReturnValue();
             }
         }
    The same holds true for static classes, with the only difference that just the declared parameters must be passed: 
         

         static class MyMethod extends RoutineMethod {

             private final Locale mLocale;

             MyMethod(final Locale locale) {
                 super(locale);
                 mLocale = locale;
             }

             String switchCase(@In final Channel<?, String> input,
                    final boolean isUpper) {
                 if (input.hasNext()) {
                     final String str = input.next();
                     return (isUpper) ? str.toUpperCase(mLocale) : str.toLowerCase(mLocale);
                 }
                 return ignoreReturnValue();
             }
         }
    The above conditions must be met also to be able to invoke the same routine several times through the call() method.

    Multiple inputs

    The routine method implementation allows for multiple input channels to deliver data to the method invocation. In such case it is possible to easily identify the channel for which an input is ready by calling the switchInput() protected method. The method will return one of the input channels passed as parameters (since the very same instance is returned == comparison is allowed) or null, if the invocation takes no input channel.

    For example, a routine printing the inputs of different types can be implemented as follows: 

         

         final Channel<Integer, Integer> inputInts = JRoutineCore.io().buildChannel();
         final Channel<String, String> inputStrings = JRoutineCore.io().buildChannel();
         final Channel<String, String> outputChannel = JRoutineCore.io().buildChannel();
         new RoutineMethod() {

             void run(@In final Channel<?, Integer> inputInts,
                     @In final Channel<?, String> inputStrings,
                     @Out final Channel<String, ?> output) {
                 final Channel<?, ?> inputChannel = switchInput();
                 if (inputChannel.hasNext()) {
                     if (inputChannel == inputInts) {
                         output.pass("Number: " + inputChannel.next());
                     } else if (inputChannel == inputStrings) {
                         output.pass("String: " + inputChannel.next());
                     }
                 }
             }
         }.call(inputInts, inputStrings, outputChannel);
         inputStrings.pass("Hello", "JRoutine", "!");
         inputInts.pass(1, 2, 3);
         outputChannel.bind(new TemplateChannelConsumer<String>() {

             @Override
             public void onOutput(final String out) {
                 System.out.println(out);
             }
         });

    Routine concatenation

    The output channels passed as parameters, or the one returned by the method, can be successfully bound to other channels in order to concatenate several routine invocations.
    The same is true for other method routines, when output channels can be passed as inputs as shown in the following example: 
         

         final Channel<Integer, Integer> inputChannel = JRoutineCore.io().buildChannel();
         final Channel<Integer, Integer> outputChannel = JRoutineCore.io().buildChannel();
         new RoutineMethod() {

             public void square(@In final Channel<?, Integer> input,
                     @Out final Channel<Integer, ?> output) {
                 if (input.hasNext()) {
                     final int i = input.next();
                     output.pass(i * i);
                 }
             }
         }.call(inputChannel, outputChannel);
         final Channel<Integer, Integer> resultChannel = JRoutineCore.io().buildChannel();
         new RoutineMethod() {

             private int mSum;

             public void sum(@In final Channel<?, Integer> input,
                     @Out final Channel<Integer, ?> output) {
                 if (input.hasNext()) {
                     mSum += input.next();
                 } else {
                     output.pass(mSum);
                 }
             }
         }.call(outputChannel, resultChannel);
         inputChannel.pass(1, 2, 3, 4).close();
         resultChannel.after(seconds(1)).next(); // expected value: 30
    Note how the input channel is closed before reading the output, since the sum routine relies on the completion notification before producing any result.
    It is also possible to feed the routine method with outputs coming from another routine. In case, for instance, a routine parsing strings into integers has already been implemented, it can be concatenated to the sum routine method as shown below: 
         

         final Channel<String, Integer> channel = parseRoutine.call();
         final Channel<Integer, Integer> outputChannel = JRoutineCore.io().buildChannel();
         new RoutineMethod() {

             private int mSum;

             public void sum(@In final Channel<?, Integer> input,
                     @Out final Channel<Integer, ?> output) {
                 if (input.hasNext()) {
                     mSum += input.next();
                 } else {
                     output.pass(mSum);
                 }
             }
         }.call(channel, outputChannel);
         channel.pass("1", "2", "3", "4").close();
         outputChannel.after(seconds(1)).next(); // expected value: 10

    Handling of abortion exception

    The routine method is notified also when one of the input or output channels is aborted.
    When that happens, channel methods used to read or write data will throw a RoutineException with the abortion reason as cause. Hence, it is possible to properly react to such event by catching the exception and inspecting it.
    Note however that, as soon as the invocation is aborted, no input can be read and no output can be passed to any of the channels.

    The following example shows how to implement a routine cleaning up external resources when the invocation completes or is aborted: 

         

         final ExternalStorage storage = ExternalStorage.create();
         final Channel<String, String> inputChannel = JRoutineCore.io().buildChannel();
         new RoutineMethod(this, storage) {

             private final StorageConnection mConnection = storage.openConnection();

             void store(@In final Channel<?, String> input) {
                 try {
                     if (input.hasNext()) {
                         mConnection.put(input.next());
                     } else {
                         mConnection.close();
                     }
                 } catch(final RoutineException e) {
                     final Throwable t = e.getCause();
                     if (t instanceof FlushConnectionException) {
                         mConnection.close();
                     } else {
                         mConnection.rollback();
                     }
                 }
             }
         }.call(inputChannel);

    Wrapping existing method

    An additional way to create a routine method is by wrapping a method of an existing object or class. The routine is created by calling one of the provided from() methods.
    No strong reference to the target object will be retained, so, it's up to the caller to ensure that it does not get garbage collected.

    Input channels can be passed to the call() method in place of the actual parameter values, though, the order and total number of inputs must match the target method signature. Moreover, all the input channels must be closed before the wrapped method is actually invoked.
    Results can be collected through the returned output channel.

    For example, a routine wrapping the String.format() method can be built as shown below: 

         

         final Channel<Object[], Object[]> inputChannel = JRoutineCore.io().buildChannel();
         final Channel<?, String> outputChannel =
                RoutineMethod.from(String.class.getMethod("format", String.class, Object[].class))
                             .call("%s %s!", inputChannel);
         inputChannel.pass(new Object[]{"Hello", "JRoutine"}).close();
         outputChannel.after(seconds(1)).next(); // expected value: "Hello JRoutine!"
    In case the very same input or output channel instance has to be passed as parameter, it has to be wrapped in another input channel, like shown below: 
         

         final Channel<String, String> channel = JRoutineCore.io().buildChannel();
         RoutineMethod.from(MyClass.class.getMethod("run", Channel.class))
                      .call(JRoutineCore.io().<Channel<String, String>>of(channel));

      • call

        @NotNull
public <OUT> Channel<?,OUT> call(@Nullable
                                          Object... params)
        Calls the routine.
        The output channel will produced the data returned by the method. In case the method does not return any output, the channel will be anyway notified of invocation abortion and completion.

        Note that the specific method will be selected based on the specified parameters. If no matching method is found, the call will fail with an exception.
        Note also that, in case no proper arguments are passed to the constructor, it will be possible to invoke this method only once.

        Type Parameters:
        OUT - the output data type.
        Parameters:
        params - the parameters.
        Returns:
        the output channel instance.
